The message handling system (MHS) directory user package
.iX "-: MHS" "message handling system"
.iX "MHS" "directory user package"
.iX "-: MHS" "MDUP"
(MDUP) contains definitions to support the use of the directory
in accordance with the standard
1988 X.400 User Agents and MTAs for name resolution,
.iX "MTA"
.iX "-: MTA" "message transfer agent"
distribution list (DL) expansion, and capability assessment.
.iX "distribution list"
.iX "-: distribution list" "DL"
The definitions are based upon
the attribute types and syntaxes specified in \*VX.402, Annex A\*O.
.P
The MDUP is an optional package that can be used by the
XDS interface.  Applications must negotiate use of this package with
\*Lds_version(\|)\*O before using any of the MDUP features.  If an
application attempts to use features specific to the package without
first negotiating its use, an appropriate error (for example,
\*LOM_NO_SUCH_CLASS\*O) is returned by the object management
(OM) function.
.P
The object identifier associated with the MDUP is
.iS
\*L{iso(1) identified-organization(3) icd-ecma(0012) member-company(2)
dec(1011) xopen(28) mdup(3)}\*O 
.iE
.P
It takes the following encoding:
.iS
\ex2B\exC\ex2\ex87\ex73\ex1C\ex3
.iE
.P
.ne 3
This identifier is represented by the constant \*LDS_MHS_DIR_USER_PKG\*O.
The C constants associated with this package are defined in 
the \*Lxdsmdup.h\*O, \*Lxmhp.h\*O, and \*Lxmsga.h\*O
header files.
.P
The concepts and notation used are first mentioned in
Chapter 11.  They are also fully explained in Chapters 17 through 19.
The attribute types are introduced first, followed
by the object classes.  Next, the OM class hierarchy and OM class
definitions required to support the new attribute types are described.
.H 2 "MDUP Attribute Types"
.P
This section presents additional directory attribute types that are used
with the MDUP.  Each attribute type has an object identifier, which
is the value of the OM attribute \*LDS_ATTRIBUTE_TYPE\*O.  These object
identifiers are represented in the interface by constants with the same
name as the directory attribute and are prefixed by \*LDS_A_\*O so that they
can be easily identified.
.P
This section contains two tables that are used to indicate the object
identifiers for MDUP attribute types (see Table 14-1),
and the values for MDUP attribute
types (see Table 14-2), respectively.  Following these two tables is 
a brief description of each attribute.  (See Chapter 12 for 
information on general matching rules).
.nS "note"
The third and fourth columns of Table 14-1 contain the contents octets
of the BER encoding of the object identifier.
All these object
identifiers stem from the root \*L{joint-iso-ccitt(2) mhs-motis(6)
arch(5) at(2)}\*O.
.nE
.P
