.VL .2i
.LI "\s-11\s0"
The value initially is the current session's attribute of the same name.
.LI "\s-12\s0"
.ne 6
If only one value is present in international communications,
its syntax is String\*L(OM_\%S_\%PRINTABLE_\%STRING)\*O.
If two values are present,
in either domestic or international communications,
the syntax of the first is String\*L(OM_\%S_\%PRINTABLE_\%STRING)\*O,
the syntax of the
second is String\*L(OM_\%S_\%TELETEX_\%STRING)\*O, 
and the two convey the same information
such that either can be safely ignored.
.sp .5
.ne 4
For example, Teletex strings allow inclusion
of the accented characters commonly used in many countries.
Not all input/output devices, however,
permit the entry and display of such characters.
Printable strings are required internationally to ensure that such
device limitations do not prevent communications.
.LI "\s-13\s0"
For 1984, the syntax of the value is
String\*L(OM_S_PRINTABLE_STRING)\*O.
.LI "\s-14\s0"
For 1984, at most one value is present.
.LI "\s-15\s0"
This attribute is present only if the
ISDN Number attribute is present.
.LI "\s-16\s0"
For 1988, this attribute is required if any
Organization Name is present.
