\*LMnemonic O/R Address\*O
.iX "O/R" "mnemonic address"
.iX "mnemonic O/R address"
.iX "-[" "O/R" "address"
.iX "-[" "address" "O/R"
.P
This address mnemonically identifies a user or DL.
Using the \*LMH_T_ADMD_NAME\*O and \*LMH_T_COUNTRY_NAME\*O attributes, it identifies an ADMD.
Using the \*LMH_T_COMMON_NAME\*O attribute or the personal name attributes,
the \*LMH_T_ORGANIZATION_NAME\*O attribute, the \*LOrganizational-Unit-Name\*O
attributes,
the \*LMH_\%T_\%PRMD_\%NAME\*O attribute, or a combination of these,
and optionally DDAs, it identifies a user or DL relative to the ADMD. 
.P
The personal name attributes identify a user or DL relative to the
entity indicated 
by another attribute; for example, \*LMH_\%T_\%ORGANIZATION_\%NAME\*O.
The \*LMH_T_SURNAME\*O attribute will be present if any of the other three
personal name attributes are present.
.LI
.ne 5
\*LNumeric O/R Address\*O
.iX "numeric O/R address"
.P
This address numerically identifies a user or DL.
Using the \*LMH_T_ADMD_NAME\*O and \*LMH_T_COUNTRY_NAME\*O attributes,
it identifies an ADMD.
Using the \*LMH_\%T_\%NUMERIC_\%USER_\%IDENTIFIER\*O attribute and possibly the
\*LMH_\%T_\%PRMD_\%NAME\*O attribute,
it identifies the user or DL relative to the ADMD.
Any DDAs provide information that is additional to that required to
identify the user or DL. 
.LI
\*LPostal O/R Address\*O
.iX "postal O/R address"
.P
This address identifies a user by means of its postal address.
Two kinds of postal O/R address are distinguished, as follows: 
.ML
.LI
Structured
.iX "structured O/R address"
.P
Said of a postal O/R address that specifies a user's postal address by
means of several attributes.
The structure of the postal address is described in the following
text in some detail.
.LI
Unstructured
.iX "unstructured O/R address"
.P
Said of a postal O/R address that specifies a user's postal
address in a single attribute.
The structure of the postal address is left largely unspecified in the
following text.
.LE
.P
Whether structured or unstructured, a postal O/R address does the following.
Using the \*LMH_\%T_\%ADMD_\%NAME\*O and \*LMH_\%T_\%COUNTRY_\%NAME\*O 
attributes, it identifies an ADMD.  Using the 
\*LMH_\%T_\%POSTAL_\%CODE\*O and \*LMH_\%T_\%POSTAL_\%COUNTRY_\%NAME\*O 
attributes, it identifies the geographical region in which the user takes 
delivery of physical messages.  Using the 
\*LMH_\%T_\%POSTAL_\%DELIV_\%SYSTEM_\%NAME\*O or 
\*LMH_\%T_\%PRMD_\%NAME\*O attribute or both,
it also may identify the PDS by means of which the user is to be accessed.
.P
An unstructured postal O/R address also includes the
\*LMH_T_POSTAL_ADDRESS_IN_FULL\*O attribute.
A structured postal O/R address also includes every other
postal addressing attribute that the PDS requires to identify
the postal patron.
.nS note
.ne 10
The total number of characters in the values of all
attributes, except for \*LMH_T_ADMD_NAME\*O, 
\*LMH_\%T_\%COUNTRY_\%NAME\*O,
and \*LMH_\%T_\%POSTAL_\%DELIV_\%SYSTEM_\%NAME\*O, in a 
postal O/R address should be
small enough to permit their rendition in 6 lines of 30 characters,
the size of a typical physical envelope window.
The rendition algorithm, while defined by the
physical delivery access unit
(PDAU), is likely to include inserting delimiters (for example, spaces)
between some attribute values.
.nE
.LI
\*LTerminal O/R Address\*O
.iX "terminal O/R address".
.iX "-]" "O/R" "address"
.iX "-]" "address" "O/R"
.P
This address identifies a user by identifying the user's terminal
using the network address attributes.
It also may identify the ADMD through which the terminal is accessed
by using the \*LMH_T_ADMD_NAME\*O and \*LMH_T_COUNTRY_NAME\*O attributes.
The \*LMH_T_PRMD_NAME\*O attribute and any DDAs,
which will be present only if the \*LMH_T_ADMD_NAME\*O and
\*LMH_T_COUNTRY_NAME\*O attributes are present,
provide information additional to that required to identify the user. 
.P
If the terminal is a Telematic terminal,
it gives the terminal's network address and possibly,
using the \*LMH_T_TERMINAL_TYPE\*O and \*LMH_T_TERMINAL_IDENTIFIER\*O attributes,
its terminal type and identifier.
If the terminal is a Telex terminal,
it gives the terminal's Telex number.
.LE
.P
Whenever two O/R addresses are compared for equality,
the following differences are ignored:
.ML
.LI
Whether an attribute has a value whose syntax 
is String\*L(OM_\%S_\%PRINTABLE_\%STRING)\*O,
a value whose syntax is String\*L(OM_\%S_\%TELETEX_\%STRING)\*O, or both.
.LI
Whether a letter in a value of an attribute not used in DDAs is
an uppercase or lowercase letter.
.LI
All leading, all trailing,
and all but one consecutive embedded space in an attribute value.
.LE
.nS note
.ne 5
An MD may impose additional equivalence rules upon the
O/R addresses it assigns to its own users and DLs.
It may define,
for example, rules concerning punctuation characters in attribute values,
the case of letters in attribute values,
or the relative order of DDAs.
.P
.ne 6
As a national matter, MDs may impose additional rules
regarding any attribute that may have a value whose syntax is
String\*L(OM_S_PRINTABLE_STRING)\*O, a value whose syntax is
String\*L(OM_S_TELETEX_STRING)\*O, or both.
In particular,
the rules for deriving from a Teletex string the equivalent
printable string may be nationally prescribed.
.nE
.H 2 "MH_C_OR_NAME"
.iX "O/R"
.P
An instance of class \*LMH_C_OR_NAME\*O comprises a directory name,
an O/R address, or both.
The name is considered present if, and only if, the
\*LMH_T_DIRECTORY_NAME\*O attribute is present.
The address comprises the attributes specific to the \*LMH_C_OR_ADDRESS\*O
class and is considered present if, and only if, at least one of
those attributes is present.
.P
An O/R name's composition is context sensitive.
At submission, the name, the address, or both may be present.
At transfer, or delivery,
the address is present and the name can (but need not) be present.
Whether at submission, transfer or delivery, the MTS uses the name,
if it is present, only if the address is absent or invalid.
.P
The attribute specific to this class is listed in Table 14-6.
.P
